Here's how to implement this in .NET MAUI Shell:

## 1. Override `OnBackButtonPressed` on your page

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            // Show dialog (fire-and-forget since override is synchronous)
            Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
            {
                bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                    "Unsaved Changes",
                    "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                    "Discard", "Stay");

                if (leave)
                    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            });

            return true; // cancel the default back navigation
        }

        return false; // allow normal navigation
    }
}
```

> **Note:** `OnBackButtonPressed` handles the hardware/system back button (Android back, etc.). It does **not** intercept the Shell navigation bar back arrow.

## 2. Hide the default back arrow and add a custom "Cancel" button

To intercept the shell toolbar back chevron, replace it with your own button:

```csharp
// In your page constructor or OnAppearing
Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior(this, new BackButtonBehavior
{
    Command = new AsyncRelayCommand(OnCancelClicked),
    TextOverride = "Cancel",
    IconOverride = null // removes the arrow icon
});
```

Then handle the command:

```csharp
private async Task OnCancelClicked()
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave) return; // stay on page
    }

    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

## 3. XAML alternative for `BackButtonBehavior`

```xml
<Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <BackButtonBehavior
        TextOverride="Cancel"
        IconOverride=""
        Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
</Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
```

## Key points

| Scenario | Mechanism |
|----------|-----------|
| Android/hardware back | `OnBackButtonPressed()` — return `true` to cancel |
| Shell toolbar back arrow | `BackButtonBehavior` with a custom `Command` |
| Swipe-back (iOS) | Disabled automatically when `BackButtonBehavior.Command` is set |

This covers both navigation vectors and gives you a "Cancel" label instead of the default chevron.
